article.description: The Timberwolves blew a big lead, missed free throws down the stretch and turned the ball over too much in the fourth quarter.
article.headline: T-Wolves have won eight of last nine games
article.linkText: T-Wolves blow lead, miss FTs, still beat Bulls
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves blew a big lead, missed free throws down the stretch and turned the ball over too much in the fourth quarter. No problem, they were playing the Chicago Bulls. Kevin Garnett had 28 points and 15 rebounds -- despite missing four straight free throws in the final two minutes -- to lead the Timberwolves to their 10th straight win over Chicago, 98-93 on Tuesday night. The Timberwolves missed nine of 16 free throws in the fourth quarter, yet won for the eighth time in nine games. "We have been a very good free throw shooting team and a low turnover team," said Minnesota coach Flip Saunders. "Two things that have been strengths for us, we struggled with." Latrell Sprewell had 27 points -- 20 in the first half -- and Sam Cassell added 21 points and nine assists for Minnesota. Minnesota's trio of Garnett, Sprewell and Cassell is the highest-scoring threesome in the NBA, averaging better than 62 points per game combined. "I stunk the game up," said Cassell, who missed two free throws and a layup in the final minute. "That's my game -- to get on the line and knock down free throws down the stretch. On Thursday (at practice), I'll be the first one on the free throw line." The Timberwolves held on despite blowing a 20-point first-half lead and turning the ball over 16 times. The Bulls stayed in it thanks to their reserves, who outscored Minnesota's 29-10. Eddy Curry, playing in just his second game since returning from a bone bruise to his knee, had 16 points before fouling out after 24 minutes. Kirk Hinrich led the Bulls with 17 points. "That's the way it's been," said Chicago's Kendall Gill, who was among six Bulls in double figures with 15 points. "We've played so many games like that, it seems like that's the norm." Chicago fought back to tie it 58-all on a three-point play by Antonio Davis with 9:01 left in the third quarter. But Cassell rallied the Timberwolves, scoring five straight points midway through the quarter as Minnesota built a 69-62 lead. Jamal Crawford, held scoreless in the first half, had 13 points after halftime to help keep the Bulls close. Crawford's three-point play with 9:35 left pulled the Bulls back within two at 81-79. Minnesota had a chance to put the game away in the final minutes but missed five of six free throw attempts over the final 2:27. Garnett was called for goaltending on a shot by Curry that brought the Bulls within 94-90 with 1:19 to play. But Cassell then scored four straight points. "We didn't play our best and we still won," Cassell said. "That's the sign of a good team." Minnesota made 11 of its first 15 shots and took a 19-11 lead on a 3-pointer by Sprewell. The Bulls scored just two points over the final five minutes of the first quarter, and the Wolves expanded their lead to 39-19 with 8:00 left in the second quarter. But Chicago came to life behind their bench, getting nine points from Eddie Robinson and eight from Curry in a 28-12 run that brought the Bulls to within 51-47 at halftime.

Game notes
Timberwolves G Troy Hudson is expected to miss at least two more weeks after aggravating his sprained right ankle against New York on Dec. 23, coach Flip Saunders said. An MRI showed scar tissue was aggravating the injury, which has forced Hudson to miss all but two games this season. ... Minnesota finished December with a 11-2 record, the best in club history. ... Tuesday's loss at Minnesota dropped the Bulls to 0-12 against the Western Conference. The Bulls have dropped 18 straight games against the West.
